<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" >
<title>Multiplying Polynomials</title>


<section>
<title>Special Binomial Products</title>


<introduction>
<p>
In the previous module we examined some elementary \gls{polynomial} multiplication. We begin
this module by considering the following polynomial multiplications, all of which will
be done using the \gls{FOIL} method. In this section, we will:
<ol>
<li><p>Multiply the sum and difference of 2 terms</p></li>
<li><p>Find the square of a \gls{binomial} sum.</p></li>
<li><p>Find the square of a binomial difference</p></li>
</ol>

</p>
</introduction>


<subsection>
<title>The FOIL method</title>
<p>
We will often be finding the product of 2 binomials, such as
<me>
  (x-2)(x+3)
</me>
so it will be useful to develop a solid place from which to start. There is a well known
acronym that can help us, which is {FOIL}. We describe it as follows
<ul>
<li><p>Multiply the  First terms from each binomial, then</p></li>
<li><p>Multiply the  Outside terms, then</p></li>
<li><p>Multiply the  Inside terms, and finally</p></li>
<li><p>Multiply the  Last terms</p></li>
</ul>
</p>

<p>
The FOIL method distributes the 1st term, and then distributes the 2nd. In the above example the
components of the FOIL are
<ul>
<li><p>{F}: the <em>first</em> terms multiplied together are <m>x\cdot x = x^2</m></p></li>
<li><p>{O}: the <em>outside</em> terms multiplied together are <m>x\cdot 3 = 3x</m></p></li>
<li><p>{I}: the <em>inside</em> terms are <m>-2\cdot x = -2x</m></p></li>
<li><p>{L}: the <em>last</em> terms are <m>-2(3)=-6</m></p></li>
</ul>
</p>

<p>
We combine all of this information as follows
<md>
  <mrow>  (x-2)(x+3) \amp  =		x^2+3x-2x-6</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		x^2+x-6</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Use the FOIL method to expand the following polynomial
<me>
  (3x+2)(4x+5)
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>
We colour code the polynomial as follows
	\begin{tightcenter}
</p>
<tabular>
<row><cell><m>({\color{red}3x}+2)({\color{red}4x}+2)</m></cell><cell>First terms {\color{red}F}</cell><cell><m>{\color{red}(3x)(4x)=12x^2}</m></cell></row>
<row><cell><m>({\color{green}3x}+2)(4x+{\color{green}5})</m></cell><cell>Outer terms {\color{green}O}</cell><cell><m>{\color{green}(3x)(5)=15x}</m></cell></row>
<row><cell><m>(3x+{\color{brown}2})({\color{brown}4x}+5)</m></cell><cell>Inner terms {\color{brown}I}</cell><cell><m>{\color{brown}(2)(4x)=8x}</m></cell></row>
<row><cell><m>(3x+{\color{blue}2})(4x+{\color{blue}{5}})</m></cell><cell>Last terms {\color{blue}L}</cell><cell><m>{\color{blue}(2)(5)=10}</m></cell></row>
</tabular>
<p>
\end{tightcenter}
	More simply, we can write
<md>
  <mrow>  (3x+2)(4x+5) \amp  =		{\color{red}12x^2}+{\color{green}15x}+{\color{brown}{8x}}+{\color{blue}{10}}</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		12x^2+23x+10</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</solution>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
\Gls{simplify} the following.

	\-\oldmarginpar[\raggedleft  Drill and skill!]	{  Drill and skill!}
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<ol>
<li><p><m>(x+1)(x+2)</m>{<m>=x^2+3x+2</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x-1)(x-4)</m>{<m>=x^2-5x+4</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(2x+1)(x-5)</m>{<m>=2x^2-9x-5</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(3x-4)(x+6)</m>{<m>=3x^2+14x-24</m>}</p></li>
</ol>
</subsection>


<subsection>
<title>Multiplying the Sum and Difference of 2 terms</title>
<p>
When using the FOIL method, there are a number of special products that arise,
for example
<me>
  (a-b)(a+b)
</me>
</p>

<p>
When using the FOIL method on a product of this form, which is the product of the sum of two terms with the product
of the difference of two terms, there is a useful simplification
<md>
  <mrow>  (a-b)(a+b) \amp  =		a^2+ab-ba-b^2</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		a^2-b^2</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>
Notice here that the `middle' terms (the Outside and the Inside terms) cancel each other out. This willbe particularly useful in later modules when we are asked to \gls{factor} a polynomial, which involves `going the other way' from FOILing.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex_sumdiff">
<statement>
<p>
Use the FOIL method to expand the following \gls{expression}
<me>
  (x-3)(x+3)
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>
We note first of all that this is the product of the sum and difference of two terms, so the middle terms will cancel. We will show the
	working for demonstration
<md>
  <mrow>  (x-3)(x+3) \amp  =		x^2+3x-3x-9</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		x^2-9</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</solution>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Simplify the following.

	\-\oldmarginpar[\raggedleft  Drill and skill!]	{  Drill and skill!}
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<ol>
<li><p><m>(x+10)(x-10)</m>{<m>=x^2-100</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x+3)(x-3)</m>{<m>=x^2-9</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x-4)(x+4)</m>{<m>=x^2-16</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x^4-7)(x^4+7)</m>{<m>=x^8-49</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(3x+1)(3x-1)</m>{<m>=9x^2-1</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(2x+4)(2x-4)</m>{<m>=4x^2-16</m>}</p></li>
</ol>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="sec_binsum">
<title>The Square of a Binomial Sum</title>
<p>
Another special case of a binomial <fn> Remember that a <em>binomial</em> is simply another way of saying a polynomial with 2 terms.</fn>
multiplication is the square of a binomial sum, for example
<me>
  (x+y)^2
</me>
</p>

<p>
Using the FOIL method on this expression, we achieve
<md>
  <mrow>  (x+y)^2 \amp  =		x^2+xy+xy+y^2</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		x^2+2xy+y^2</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>
In words: The square of a binomial sum is the first term squared, plus two times the product of the terms, plus the last term squared.
</p>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Use the FOIL method to expand the following polynomial
<me>
  (2x+5)^2
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>
We apply the FOIL method and obtain
<md>
  <mrow>  (2x+5)^2 \amp  =		(2x)^2+(2x)(5)+(2x)(5)+5^2</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		4x^2+10x+10x+25</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		4x^2+20x+25</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</solution>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Simplify the following.

	\-\oldmarginpar[\raggedleft  Drill and skill!]	{  Drill and skill!}
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<ol>
<li><p><m>(x+1)^2</m>{<m>=x^2+2x+1</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x+6)^2</m>{<m>=x^2+12x+36</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x+10)^2</m>{<m>=x^2+20x+100</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x+7)^2</m>{<m>=x^2+14x+49</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x^2+9)^2</m>{<m>=x^4+18x^2+81</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(2x+4)^2</m>{<m>=4x^2+16x+16</m>}</p></li>
</ol>
</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="sec_bindiff">
<title>The Square of a Binomial Difference</title>
<p>
The final special case of a binomial multiplication is the square of a binomial difference, for example
<me>
  (x-2)^2
</me>
</p>

<p>
Using the FOIL method gives
<md>
  <mrow>  (x-2)^2 \amp  =		x^2-2x-2x+4</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		x^2-4x+4</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>
In general
<me>
  (x-y)^2 = x^2-2xy+y^2
</me>
</p>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Use the FOIL method to expand the following polynomial
<me>
  (4x-6)^2
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>
On applying the FOIL procedure, we obtain
<md>
  <mrow>  (4x-6)^2 \amp  =		(4x)^2+(4x)(-6)+(4x)(-6)+(-6)^2</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		16x^2 - 24x - 24x +36</mrow>
  <mrow>  \amp  =		16x^2-48x+36</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</solution>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Simplify the following.

	\-\oldmarginpar[\raggedleft  Drill and skill!]	{  Drill and skill!}
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<ol>
<li><p><m>(x-1)^2</m>{<m>=x^2-2x+1</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x-6)^2</m>{<m>=x^2-12x+36</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x-10)^2</m>{<m>=x^2-20x+100</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x-7)^2</m>{<m>=x^2-14x+49</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x^2-9)^2</m>{<m>=x^4-18x^2+81</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(2x-4)^2</m>{<m>=4x^2-16x+16</m>}</p></li>
</ol>
</subsection>


