<subsection>
<title>The cube of a binomial sum</title>
<p>
We can find the <em>cube</em> of a binomial sum by using the FOIL technique combined
with polynomial multiplication.
</p>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Expand the following polynomial by using polynomial multiplication
<me>
  (x+y)^3
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>
<m>\begin{aligned}(x+y)^3 \amp  = (x+y)(x+y)^2\\
\amp  = (x+y)(x^2+2xy+y^2)\\
\amp  = x^3+2x^2y+xy^2 + yx^2 + 2xy^2 + y^3\\
\amp  = x^3 + 3x^2y + 3 xy^2 + y^3
\end{aligned}</m>
</p>
</solution>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Here are some miscellaneous short-cut cube examples.

	\-\oldmarginpar[\raggedleft  Drill and skill!]	{  Drill and skill!}
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>

<ol>
<li><p><m>(x+1)^3</m>{<m>=x^3+3x^2+3x+1</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x+2)^3</m>{<m>=x^3+6x^2+12x+8</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(2x+3)^3</m>{<m>=8x^3+36x^2+54x+27</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(3x+2y)^3</m>{<m>=27x^3+54x^2y+36x*y^2+8y^3</m>}</p></li>
</ol>

</p>
</solution>
</subsection>


<subsection>
<title>The cube of a binomial difference</title>
<p>
We can find the <em>cube</em> of a binomial difference by using the FOIL technique combined
with polynomial multiplication- this is very similar to the technique used for the
cube of binomial sum.
</p>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Expand the following polynomial by using polynomial multiplication
<me>
  (x-y)^3
</me>
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>
<m>\begin{aligned}(x-y)^3 \amp  = (x-y)(x-y)^2\\
\amp  = (x-y)(x^2-2xy+y^2)\\
\amp  = x^3-2x^2y+xy^2 - yx^2 + 2xy^2 - y^3\\
\amp  = x^3 -3x^2y + 3 xy^2 - y^3
\end{aligned}</m>
</p>
</solution>

<example>
<statement>
<p>
Here are some miscellaneous short-cut cube examples.

	\-\oldmarginpar[\raggedleft  Drill and skill!]	{  Drill and skill!}
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>

<ol>
<li><p><m>(x-1)^3</m>{<m>=x^3-3x^2+3x-1</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(x+2)^3</m>{<m>=x^3-6x^2+12x-8</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(2x+3)^3</m>{<m>=8x^3-36x^2+54x-27</m>}</p></li>
<li><p><m>(3x+2y)^3</m>{<m>=27x^3-54x^2y+36x*y^2-8y^3</m>}</p></li>
</ol>

</p>
</solution>
</subsection>


<subsection>
<title>An application</title>
<p>
The following is an application of our work in polynomials.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex_fallingobject">
<statement>
<p>
Consider the \gls{equation} of motion for an object tossed straight up into the air (projected vertically),
or dropped (falling)
<men xml:id="eq_objectfalling" >
  s = -\frac{1}{2}gt^2+v_0t+s_0
</men>
</p>

<p>
Note the following:
<ul>
<li><p><m>s</m> is vertical position (height above ground) of the tossed object in feet (ft)</p></li>
<li><p><m>g</m> is the acceleration due to gravity (and we will assume <m>g=32</m>)</p></li>
<li><p><m>t</m> is time in seconds that the object has been in motion (seconds)</p></li>
<li><p><m>v_0</m> is the initial speed (or velocity) of the object in ft/sec</p></li>
<li><p><m>s_0</m> is the initial position at time <m>t=0</m></p></li>
</ul>
</p>

<p>
Find the height of ball after
<ol>
<li><p><m>2</m> seconds</p></li>
<li><p><m>4</m> seconds</p></li>
<li><p><m>6</m> seconds</p></li>
</ol>

</p>
</statement>
</example>

<solution>
<p>
Before we begin this example, we first need to rewrite <xref ref="eq_objectfalling" autoname="yes" /> using
	the given information. It becomes
<me>
  s = -16t^2+80t+96
</me>
</p>

<p>
To find the height of the object at each of the specified times, we will simply replace <m>t</m> by 2, 4, and 6 seconds in turn.
<ol>
<li><p>After 2 seconds, the height of the object (in feet) is
<me>
  -16(2^2)+80(-2)+96 = 192
</me></p></li>
<li><p>After 4 seconds, the height of the object (in feet) is
<me>
  -16(4^2)+80(4)+96=160
</me></p></li>
<li><p>After 6 seconds, the height of the object (in feet) is
<me>
  -16(6^2)+80(6)+96=0
</me></p></li>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
We clearly see that as time increase, the height of the object is decreasing. In fact, after
	6 seconds the ball is at a height of 0ft above the ground- in other words it has hit the ground
	at this time.
				
	<xref ref="fig_fallingobject2" autoname="yes" /> shows a visual representation of the height of the object thrown in
	the example considered so far.
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig_fallingobject2" >
<caption>A falling object</caption>
<image>
<latex-image-code><![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}\begin{axis}[
					framed,
					axis line style={->},
					xmin=-1,xmax=10,
					ymin=-20,ymax=200,
					xlabel={\(t\)},
					ylabel={\(s\)},
					xtick={0,2,...,8},
					ytick={0,20,...,180},
					grid=major,
					scatter/classes={a={mark=*,draw=violet,fill=violet,scale=1},
						b={mark=*,draw=red,fill=red,scale=1},
						c={mark=*,draw=black,fill=black,scale=1},
						d={scale=0}}
				]
				\addplot[red]expression[domain=0:6,samples=100]{-16*x^2+80*x+96};
			\end{axis}\end{tikzpicture}]]></latex-image-code>
</image>

</figure>
<p>
\FloatBarrier
				
	The horizontal axis represents the object's time in seconds. The vertical axis represents
	the object's height above the ground.
<ul>
<li><p>During which time period is the object increasing in height? 

		We see that the height is increasing from <m>t=0</m> to approximately
		<m>t=2.5</m> seconds.</p></li>
<li><p>During which time period is the object decreasing in height?

		We see that the height is decreasing from approximately <m>t=2.5</m> seconds
		to <m>t=6</m> seconds.</p></li>
<li><p>After how much time does the object strike the ground?

		The object strikes the ground when the graph cuts the horizontal
		axis, which happens when <m>t=6</m>.</p></li>
<li><p>After how many seconds does the object reach its maximum height? Give an
		approximation of this height.

		The maximum value of the height (which we will later discuss as the <em>\gls{vertex}</em> of
		the graph) occurs when <m>t \approx 2.5</m>, and looking at the vertical scale, we see
		that the maximum height is approximately 195ft.</p></li>
</ul>

</p>
</solution>
